<body>

<section>
    <h2>1. Introduction</h2>
    <p>
        Statistical inference is the process of drawing conclusions about a population
        based on information obtained from a sample. It forms the basis of decision
        making under uncertainty.
    </p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>2. Basic Terminologies of Hypothesis Testing</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><b>Population:</b> Entire set of individuals or observations.</li>
        <li><b>Sample:</b> Subset selected from the population.</li>
        <li><b>Null Hypothesis (H₀):</b> Statement of no effect or no difference.</li>
        <li><b>Alternative Hypothesis (H₁):</b> Statement contradicting H₀.</li>
        <li><b>Level of Significance (α):</b> Probability of rejecting H₀ when it is true.</li>
        <li><b>Test Statistic:</b> Value calculated from sample data.</li>
        <li><b>P-value:</b> Probability of observing the test result under H₀.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>3. Confidence Interval</h2>
    <p>
        A confidence interval provides a range of values within which the population
        parameter is expected to lie with a certain level of confidence.
    </p>

    <div class="highlight">
        <b>Formula (Mean):</b><br>
        Confidence Interval = x̄ ± Z<sub>α/2</sub> (σ / √n)
    </div>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>4. Sample Size Determination</h2>
    <p>
        Sample size determination ensures that the sample is adequate to estimate
        population parameters accurately.
    </p>

    <div class="highlight">
        <b>Formula:</b><br>
        n = (Z<sub>α/2</sub>² × σ²) / E²
    </div>

    <p>
        where E is the allowable error.
    </p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>5. Hypothesis Test for Proportions</h2>
    <p>
        This test is used to check whether a population proportion differs from a
        specified value.
    </p>

    <div class="highlight">
        <b>Test Statistic:</b><br>
        Z = (p̂ − p) / √[pq / n]
    </div>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>6. Hypothesis Test for Mean (Single Sample)</h2>
    <p>
        This test is used to test the mean of a single population.
    </p>

    <div class="highlight">
        <b>Z-test Statistic:</b><br>
        Z = (x̄ − μ) / (σ / √n)
    </div>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>7. Hypothesis Test for Difference of Means</h2>
    <p>
        This test compares the means of two populations to check if there is a
        significant difference.
    </p>

    <div class="highlight">
        <b>Test Statistic:</b><br>
        Z = (x̄₁ − x̄₂) / √[(σ₁² / n₁) + (σ₂² / n₂)]
    </div>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>Conclusion</h2>
    <p>
        Statistical inference provides tools for making decisions based on data.
        Confidence intervals and hypothesis testing are essential techniques for
        analyzing population parameters using sample data.
    </p>
</section>

